  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to Poems from the Yeokgang Banquet
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year of His Majesty's reign, in the eleventh month of late autumn in the year Sinmi, our beloved master Han-san, the Hermit of Mok-eun, received the royal summons to journey to the capital. Along the way, he stopped at a villa on the Yeokgang River, where Provincial Inspector An offered wine in his honor. As the sun descended and the sky cleared with moonlight brilliant, we set our boat upon the river's midst and reveled until the gathering dissolved. By the next morning, ice had formed upon the water, making passage impossible. Yet after a day had passed, an official dispatch arrived bearing the royal command: "Han-san's count Saek remains between Chungju and Yeoju. The Provincial Inspector shall ensure provisions and horses are prepared with utmost propriety and care." Inspector An humbly received this command and promptly arranged another feast. That day, clouds gathered and snow fell softly, while the river's ice spontaneously thawed. Our master and Inspector An embarked together, drifting with the current. Among those assembled were Signary Chong Hak, the master's own son; the Governor of Yeohung, Gwon Chong, his nephew; Li U, a regional official, and myself—all disciples of our master. As offerings and courtesies were exchanged with growing warmth, the moon gleamed softly through the clouds, the water stretched boundless toward heaven, gentle waves bore not a ripple, and snowflakes descended intermittently—truly a sublime moment upon the water.

    The following day, Scholar Tao-jae Li, bearing a commission from the Royal Academy, arrived swiftly and joined us for another river excursion. Tao-jae stands as a great literary master of our age, and it was our master who selected him as the highest scholar in the examination of the year Sinhae. Inspector An descends from the venerable Minister Ssangchong and shares generational bonds with our master through their simultaneous advancement—a friendship of deep foundation. An has long been known for his moral conduct and careful restraint, advancing through offices of prominence. Now, bearing heavy responsibility as guardian of a province, he labors to bring prosperity to the people and shine forth the virtue of the crown. Witnessing our master summoned to court, how could he not bend all his sincerity to honor this occasion and fulfill the sovereign's gracious intent? Thus moved by his genuine heart, the ice itself dissolved, granting us this day's joy upon the waters—is it not beautiful?

    The beauty of Yeokgang's landscape has been celebrated since ancient times. Yet human affairs rarely align as we wish, and it is difficult for kindred spirits to gather in one place. For us, scattered as we have been, to find such reunion is truly rare fortune. And for Inspector An, bound by the responsibilities of his high office and endless duties, such opportunity is scarcely won. How much more remarkable then that in the depths of winter's bitter cold we float and make merry as we do this day—who knows how many times such gatherings may occur? To sit together with worthies of Han-san's moral stature, An's commanding presence, Tao-jae's elegant learning, and such eminent and capable gentlemen—how few times has the heaven and earth witnessed this? Since this river first flowed, truly this gathering stands unique. That I, possessing no talent, should participate in this occasion fills me with gratitude. Therefore I cannot let this pass unrecorded and humbly present this quatrain in long meter to the Provincial Inspector, submitting it with deepest humility.
  footnotes:
    - The year Sinmi refers to 1391, the third year of the reign of King Taejo of Joseon.
    - Han-san (韓山), whose personal name was Saek (穡), was known as the Hermit of Mok-eun (木隱先生)—a revered Confucian scholar and official.
    - The Yeokgang (驪江) River connects the regions of Chungju and Yeoju, significant locations during the early Joseon period.
    - The examination of year Sinhae (辛亥, 1371) refers to civil service examinations under the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.
    - Minister Ssangchong (雙淸相國) represents a lineage of high officials whose connections bind these worthy figures together across generations.
    - The 'four-rhyme quatrain in long meter' (長句四韻詩) was a prestigious poetic form favored in classical East Asian literary circles.
